==English==

===Etymology 1===
Middle English ''[[defoulen]]'', ''[[defoilen]]'', Old French ''[[defouler]]'', "to trample upon".

====Verb====
{{en-infl-reg-other-e|defil|e}}

# ''(transitive)'' to [[impure]]; to make [[dirty]].  Less strong than ''to [[pollute]]''

===Etymology 2===
Earlier ''[[defilee]]'', French ''[[défilé]]'', from ''[[défiler]]'', "to march past", from ''[[file]]'', "file".

====Noun====
{{en-noun-reg}}

# A [[way]] or [[gorge]] so [[narrow]] that only one person [[at a time]] can [[pass]].

=====See also=====
*[[glen]]

====Verb====
{{en-infl-reg-other-e|defil|e}}

# {{obsolete}} ''(intransitive)'' To [[march]] in a [[single]] [[file]].

